				<h3 id="post-4016"><a href="http://samablog.robsama.com/?p=4016" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent Link to Your Brother&#8217;s Keeper">Your Brother&#8217;s Keeper</a></h3>
				<small>Sunday, February 22nd, 2009</small>

				<div class="entry">
					<p>On objecting to bailing out your neighbors profligacy:</p>
<blockquote><p>Many others take a harsher view, objecting to the idea of taxpayer money going to help people who borrowed and spent without regard to consequences. &#8220;I don&#8217;t appreciate paying for someone else&#8217;s mortgage,&#8221; said Ashling Gowell, 38, a stay-at-home mother who lives in southeastern Massachusetts. <strong>&#8220;I almost feel its bailing out someone who overspent on their credit card.&#8221;</strong></p></blockquote>
<p>Just you wait Ashling.  That&#8217;s coming next.</p>
<p>Read the whole thing <a href="http://www.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/articles/2009/02/22/bailout_lament_what_about_me/?page=full">here</a>.</p>
<p>(via <a href="http://pajamasmedia.com/instapundit/70844/">Instapundit</a>)</p>
				</div>

